  "issue_title": "[BUG] calculate_issue_multiplier picks valid_issues[0] \u2014 GraphQL ordering decides maintainer vs standard multiplier",
  "issue_body": "## Description\n\n`calculate_issue_multiplier` at [scoring.py:442-449](gittensor/validator/oss_contributions/scoring.py#L442-L449) picks `valid_issues[0]` to decide between maintainer (1.66\u00d7) and standard (1.33\u00d7) multiplier. `pr.issues` comes from GraphQL `closingIssuesReferences.nodes` in insertion order, which isn't documented as stable \u2014 so when a PR closes both a maintainer-authored and a regular-author valid issue, the multiplier depends on GitHub's response ordering.\n\n## Impact\n\n- Multiplier flips between 1.33\u00d7 and 1.66\u00d7 (~25% score swing) based on GraphQL ordering.\n- Perverse incentive: closing *more* valid issues can *lower* the multiplier. A miner who closes only the maintainer issue gets 1.66\u00d7; a miner who also closes an incidental user issue may get 1.33\u00d7 depending on order.\n\n## Precedent\n\nIssue-discovery already normalises this list by sorting on `created_at` at [issue_discovery/scoring.py:213-217](gittensor/validator/issue_discovery/scoring.py#L213-L217). The OSS path has no equivalent. Same class of determinism bug as #633 (label ordering).\n\n## Suggested fix\n\nIn `calculate_issue_multiplier`, pick the max multiplier across `valid_issues` (maintainer-first). Honours the intent of `MAINTAINER_ISSUE_MULTIPLIER` and removes the ordering dependency.\n",
  "merged_at": "2026-04-22T14:52:33.000Z",
